# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: black-sox-scandal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1884 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished fifth in the American Association with a record of 68–41, 8 games behind the New York Metropolitans.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were looking to return to their 1882 form, when they won the American Association pennant before falling to third place in 1883.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club named pitcher Will White the player-manager for the 1884 season, taking over for catcher Pop Snyder.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season, although they did sign Tom Mansell, who had split the previous season between the Detroit Wolverines of the National League, and the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns of the AA, hitting .305 with 34 RBI and 45 runs between those two teams.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club also moved into American Park for the 1884 season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly was the offensive force on the team, hitting .339 with eleven home runs and 91 RBI, all club highs.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones hit .314 with seven home runs and 71 RBI, along with a team high 117 runs.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White led the way with a 34–18 record and a 3.32 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati got off to a slow start, as they lost their first game in their new ballpark, 10–9 to the Columbus Buckeyes, and they had a record of 4–5 in their first nine games, before reeling off four wins in a row to stay above the .500 level for the rest of the season.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got red hot, as they eventually had a 28–14 record, only one game out of first place.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] In a three-game series against the Washington Nationals, the Red Stockings outscored their opposition 48–6.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started to fade as the season continued on, and with their record at 44–27 changed managers, bringing Pop Snyder back as player-manager.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati continued to slump, falling to 10½ games out of first place with a 52–35 record, but then won ten games in a row to climb back to within 4½ games.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was too little too late though, as Cincinnati finished the season with a 68–41 record, good enough for fifth place, eight games behind the Metropolitans.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1885 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished second in the American Association, 16 games behind the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the Red Stockings hired O.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Caylor to become the manager of the team, the first time in club history that the club did not have a player-manager.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed Tony Mullane to a contract.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane, who spent the 1884 season with the Toledo Blue Stockings, had a 36–26 record with a 2.52 ERA in 67 starts, striking out 325 batters.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane was suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, as the Blue Stockings and the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons, another team he tried to sign with, folded after the 1884 season, and the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns attempted to reclaim Mullane, as he pitched there in 1883.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the Browns could reclaim him, he signed with the Red Stockings.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Frank Fennelly, who the Red Stockings acquired late in the 1884 season from the Washington Nationals, had a breakout season, hitting .273 with ten home runs and a league high 89 RBI.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones led the team with a .322 average, and had five home runs and 35 RBI to go along with it, while John Reilly hit .297 with five homers and 60 RBI.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Larry McKeon led the Red Stockings with 20 wins and a 2.86 ERA in 33 starts, while Will White had eighteen wins and a 3.53 ERA in 34 starts.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season very well, putting up an impressive 16–8 record in their first 24 games to sit in second place in the league, two games behind the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then began to slump, as they would win only six of their next sixteen games to slip into third place, seven games behind the Browns.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On July 1, the Red Stockings acquired Jim Keenan and Larry McKeon, who both jumped from the Detroit Wolverines to join Cincinnati.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings improved with their new acquisitions in the lineup, as the team eventually moved back into second place, however, they were too far behind the Browns, and Cincinnati finished the season with a 63–49 record, good for second place, however, they were sixteen games out of first.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:black-sox-scandal/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] There is strong evidence both for and against Rothstein's involvement; however, there is no conclusive indication that the syndicate's actions were directed by or involved organized crime.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In response to the scandal, the National Baseball Commission was dissolved and Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis was appointed to be the first commissioner of baseball, given absolute control over the sport to restore its integrity.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Despite acquittals in a public trial in 1921, Landis permanently banned all eight implicated players from professional baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Baseball Hall of Fame eventually defined the punishment as banishment from consideration for the Hall.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Despite requests for reinstatement in the decades that followed (particularly in the case of Shoeless Joe Jackson), the ban remained in force for more than a century.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In 2025, Commissioner Rob Manfred reinstated the Black Sox and several other now-deceased players.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In 1919, Charles Comiskey, the owner of the Chicago White Sox and a prominent Major League Baseball (MLB) player from 1882 to 1894, was widely resented by his players for his miserliness.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey long had a reputation for underpaying players, even though the White Sox were one of the top teams in the league and had already won the 1917 World Series.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] This was a marked turnabout from Comiskey's days as a player, when he took part in the Players' League labor rebellion in 1890.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey was probably no worse than most owners of the time; in fact, the White Sox had the largest team payroll in 1919.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In the era of the reserve clause, gamblers could find players on many teams looking for extra cash—and did.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The White Sox clubhouse was divided into two factions.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] One group resented the more straitlaced players (later called the "Clean Sox"), a group that included second baseman Eddie Collins, catcher Ray Schalk, and pitchers Red Faber and Dickie Kerr.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] By contemporary accounts, the two factions rarely spoke to each other on or off the field, and the only thing they had in common was a resentment of Comiskey.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On September 18, 1919, White Sox player Chick Gandil met with Joe "Sport" Sullivan, a Boston bookmaker, at the Hotel Buckminster near Fenway Park.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The two men discussed plans to throw their upcoming series with the Cincinnati Reds for $80,000 ($1,575,000 in September 2025).
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Two days later, a meeting of White Sox players—including those committed to going ahead with the fix and those just ready to listen to the proposal—took place in Gandil's room at the Ansonia Hotel in New York City.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Buck Weaver, the team's third baseman, was the only player to attend the meetings who did not receive money; nevertheless, he was later banned along with the other seven Black Sox for knowing about the fix but not reporting it.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Although he hardly played in the series, utility infielder Fred McMullin heard about the fix and threatened to report the others unless he was in on the payoff.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] As a small coincidence, McMullin was a former teammate of retired player William "Sleepy Bill" Burns, who had a minor role in the fix.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Both had played for the Los Angeles Angels of the Pacific Coast League (PCL), and Burns had previously pitched for the White Sox in 1909 and 1910.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Star outfielder "Shoeless Joe" Jackson was mentioned as a participant but did not attend the meetings, and his involvement remains disputed.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The scheme got an unexpected boost when the straitlaced Faber could not pitch due to getting sick with the flu.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Years later, Schalk said the fix would not have happened if Faber had been available.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] According to Schalk, since Faber was the ace of the staff, he would almost certainly have gotten starts that went instead to two of the alleged conspirators, pitchers Eddie "Knuckles" Cicotte and Lefty Williams.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On October 1, the day of Game One, there were rumors amongst gamblers that the World Series was fixed, and a sudden influx of money being bet on Cincinnati caused the odds against them to fall rapidly.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] These rumors also reached the press box where several correspondents, including Hugh Fullerton of the *Chicago Herald and Examiner* and ex-player and manager Christy Mathewson, resolved to compare notes on any plays and players that they felt were questionable.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, most fans and observers were taking the series at face value.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After throwing a strike with his first pitch of the Series, Cicotte's second pitch struck Cincinnati leadoff hitter Morrie Rath in the back, delivering a pre-arranged signal confirming the players' willingness to go through with the fix.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In the fourth inning, Cicotte made a bad throw to Swede Risberg at second base.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Sportswriters found the unsuccessful double play to be suspicious.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Williams lost three games, a Series record.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Kerr, a rookie who was not part of the fix, won both of his starts.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, the gamblers were now reneging on their promised progress payments (to be paid after each game lost), claiming that all the money was let out on bets and was in the hands of the bookmakers.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After Game Five, angry about the non-payment of promised money, the players involved in the fix attempted to doublecross the gamblers and won Games Six and Seven of the best-of-nine Series.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Before Game Eight, threats of violence were made on the gamblers' behalf against players and family members.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Williams started Game Eight but gave up four straight one-out hits for three runs before manager Kid Gleason relieved him.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The White Sox lost Game Eight (and the series) on October 9, 1919.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Besides Weaver, the players involved in the scandal received $5,000 each (equivalent to $93,000 in 2025) or more, with Gandil taking $35,000 (equivalent to $650,000 in 2025).
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Rumors of the fix dogged the White Sox throughout the 1920 season as they battled the Cleveland Indians for the American League pennant, and stories of corruption touched players on other clubs as well.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] At last, in September 1920, a grand jury was convened to investigate; Cicotte confessed to his participation in the fix to the grand jury on September 28.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On the eve of their final season series, the White Sox were in a virtual tie for first place with the Indians.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Sox would need to win all three of their remaining games and then hope for Cleveland to stumble, as the Indians had more games left to play than the Sox.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Despite the season being on the line, Comiskey suspended the seven White Sox still in the majors (Gandil had not returned to the team in 1920 and was playing semi-pro ball).
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He later said he had no choice but to suspend them, even though this action likely cost the Sox any chance of winning a second pennant.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Sox lost two of the three games in the final series against the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Louis Browns and finished in second place, two games behind the Indians, who went on to win the 1920 World Series.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The grand jury issued its decision on October 22, 1920, and eight players and five gamblers were implicated.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The indictments included nine counts of conspiracy to defraud.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The ten players not implicated in the scandal, as well as manager Kid Gleason, were each given $1,500 bonus checks (equivalent to $24,100 in 2025) by Comiskey in October 1920, the amount equaling the difference between the winners' and losers' share for participation in the 1919 Series.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The trial commenced in Chicago on June 27, 1921, but was delayed by Judge Hugo Friend because two defendants, Ben Franklin and Carl Zork, claimed to be ill.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Right fielder Shano Collins was named as the wronged party in the indictments, accusing his corrupt teammates of having cost him $1,784 as a result of the scandal.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Before the trial, key evidence went missing from the Cook County courthouse, including the signed confessions of Cicotte and Jackson, who subsequently recanted their confessions.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Some years later, the missing confessions reappeared in the possession of Comiskey's lawyer.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On July 1, the prosecution announced that Burns, who was under indictment for his part in the scandal, had turned state's evidence and would testify.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] During jury selection on July 11, several members of the current White Sox team, including Gleason, visited the courthouse, chatting and shaking hands with the indicted ex-players; at one point they even tickled Weaver, who was known to be quite ticklish.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Jury selection took several days, but on July 15 twelve jurors were finally empaneled in the case.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Trial testimony began on July 18, when prosecutor Charles Gorman outlined the evidence he planned to present against the defendants.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey was then called to the stand, and became so agitated with questions being posed by the defense that he rose from the witness chair and shook his fist at the defendants' counsel, Ben Short.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After additional testimony and evidence, on July 28 the defense rested and the case went to the jury.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The jury deliberated for less than three hours before returning verdicts of not guilty on all charges for all of the accused players.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Long before the scandal broke, many of baseball's owners had nursed longstanding grievances with the way the game was then governed by the National Baseball Commission.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The Black Sox scandal and the damage it caused to the game's reputation gave owners the resolve to make significant changes to the governance of the sport.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Their original plan was to appoint the widely respected federal judge and noted baseball fan Kenesaw Mountain Landis to head a reformed three-member commission comprising men unconnected to baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, Landis made it clear to the owners that he would accept only an appointment as the game's sole commissioner, and even then only on the condition that he be granted essentially unchecked power over the sport.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Desperate to clean up the game's image, the owners agreed to his terms and vested him with virtually unlimited authority over everyone in the major and minor leagues.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] It was controversial at the time for MLB to move toward a single commissioner with sole governance on behalf of the owners.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Following their acquittals, Landis quickly quashed any prospect that he might reinstate the accused players.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Making use of a precedent that had previously seen Babe Borton, Harl Maggert, Gene Dale and Bill Rumler banned from the PCL for fixing games, Landis made it clear that all eight accused players would remain on the "ineligible list," banning them from organized baseball.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Landis took the position that while the players had been acquitted in court, there was no dispute they had broken the rules of baseball, and none of them could ever be allowed back in the game if it were to regain the public's trust.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey supported Landis by giving the seven who remained under contract to the White Sox their unconditional release.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Following the commissioner's statement, it was universally understood that all eight implicated players were to be banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He established the precedent that the league vested the commissioner with plenary power and the responsibility to determine the fitness or suitability of anyone, anything, or any circumstance, to be associated with professional baseball, past, present and future.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Also banned was Joe Gedeon, second baseman for the St.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] A friend of Risberg, Gedeon learned about the fix from Risberg and placed bets on Cincinnati.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He informed Comiskey of the fix after the Series to gain a reward.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Instead, Landis banned him for life along with the eight White Sox.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] The extent of Jackson's part in the scheme remains controversial.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] He had a Series-leading .375 batting average—including the Series' only home run—threw out five baserunners and handled thirty chances in the outfield with no errors.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In general, players perform worse in games their team loses, and Jackson batted worse in the five games that the White Sox lost, with a batting average of .286 in losing games.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] This was still an above-average batting average (the National and American Leagues hit a combined .263 in the 1919 season).
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Jackson hit .351 for the season, fourth-best in the major leagues (his .356 career batting average is the fourth-best in history, surpassed only by Ty Cobb, Oscar Charleston and Rogers Hornsby) – each an MLB batting average leader.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Three of his six RBIs came in the losses, including the aforementioned home run, and a double in Game Eight when the Reds had a significant lead and the series was all but over.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Still, in that game, a long foul ball was caught at the fence with runners on second and third, depriving Jackson of a chance to drive in the runners.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] One play in particular has been subjected to scrutiny.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] In the fifth inning of Game Four, with a Cincinnati player on second, Jackson fielded a single hit to left field and threw home, which was cut off by Cicotte.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Gandil later admitted to yelling at Cicotte to intercept the throw.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Cicotte, whose guilt is undisputed, made two errors in that fifth inning alone.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Years later, all the implicated players said that Jackson was never present at their meetings with the gamblers.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Williams, Jackson's roommate, later said they mentioned Jackson only in hopes of giving them more credibility with the gamblers.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] After being banned, Risberg and several other members of the Black Sox tried to organize a three-state barnstorming tour.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] However, they were forced to cancel those plans after Landis let it be known that anyone who played with or against them would also be banned from baseball for life.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] They then announced plans to play a regular exhibition game every Sunday in Chicago, but the Chicago City Council threatened to cancel the license of any ballpark that hosted them.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] With seven of their best players permanently sidelined, the White Sox crashed into seventh place in 1921 and would not be a contender in a pennant race again until 1936, five years after Comiskey's death.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] They would not win another American League championship until 1959 (a then-record forty-year gap) nor another World Series until 2005, prompting some to comment about a Curse of the Black Sox.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Although many believe the Black Sox name to be related to the dark and corrupt nature of the conspiracy, the term "Black Sox" may already have existed before the fix.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] There is a story that the name "Black Sox" derived from Comiskey's refusal to pay for the players' uniforms to be laundered, instead insisting that the players themselves pay for the cleaning.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] As the story goes, the players refused, and subsequent games saw the White Sox play in progressively filthier uniforms as dirt, sweat and grime collected on the white, woolen uniforms until they took on a much darker shade.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] Comiskey then had the uniforms washed and deducted the laundry bill from the players' salaries.
[src:black-sox-scandal/black-sox-scandal] On the other hand, Eliot Asinof in his book *Eight Men Out* makes no such connection, mentioning the filthy uniforms early on but referring to the term "Black Sox" only in connection with the scandal.
